## APKTool

What it is: A tool for reverse engineering Android APK files - it decodes resources to nearly original form and rebuilds them after modifications.

## Key Features
  -Decodes resources (layouts, images, strings) to original form
  -Rebuilds decoded resources back to APK
  -Allows modification of app resources
  -Useful for smali (Dalvik bytecode) debugging

## Primary Use

# Decode APK to read resources
apktool d app.apk -o decoded/

# Modify resources (e.g., change strings.xml)
nano decoded/res/values/strings.xml

# Rebuild APK after changes
apktool b decoded/ -o modified.apk

## What You Can Find
  -AndroidManifest.xml: Permissions, exported components, debug flags
  -Resources: Hardcoded URLs in strings.xml, certificate files in assets
  -Smali code: Low-level bytecode when Java decompilation fails
  -Layout files: UI components that might leak data

## Key Difference from JADX
  -APKTool focuses on resources (XML, assets, images)
  -JADX focuses on code (converting DEX to Java)
  -Best practice: Use both together

## Common Use Cases

# Extract all strings to find API endpoints
grep -r "https://" decoded/res/values/strings.xml

# Check for debug flag
cat decoded/AndroidManifest.xml | grep debuggable

# Find exported components
cat decoded/AndroidManifest.xml | grep "exported=true"

